1. Forms
Form Tag
<form action="#">
</form>

Used to collect user input.

Input Types
<input type="text">
<input type="password">
<input type="email">
<input type="number">
Required Attribute
<input type="text" required>
Makes the field mandatory.
Form cannot be submitted if empty.
Label Tag
<label for="username">Username</label>
<input type="text" id="username">

Why use it?

Improves accessibility.
Clicking the label focuses the input.
Radio Button vs Checkbox
Radio Button
<input type="radio">
Select only one option.

Example:

○ Male
○ Female
Checkbox
<input type="checkbox">
Select multiple options.

Example:

☑ Java
☑ DSA
☐ Web Dev
2. GET vs POST
GET
<form method="GET">
Data visible in URL.
Used for searching/filtering.
Less secure.
POST
<form method="POST">
Data not visible in URL.
Used for login/signup.
More secure.
3. Semantic Tags

Semantic tags provide meaning to content.

Common Semantic Tags
<header>
<nav>
<main>
<section>
<article>
<footer>
div vs Semantic Tags
div
<div></div>
No meaning.
Used mainly for layout.
Semantic Tag
<section></section>
Gives meaning to content.
Better for SEO and accessibility.
4. section vs article
Section

Groups related content.

<section>
    <h2>Courses</h2>
</section>
Article

Independent content.

<article>
    Java Course
</article>

Example:

<section>
    <article>Java Course</article>
    <article>Web Dev Course</article>
    <article>DSA Course</article>
</section>
5. Why Semantic Tags Matter for SEO
Easier for search engines to understand content.
Improves accessibility.
Better website structure.
